","meanings":["English: variant of   Moores  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","French, Flemish, and Walloon: from a vernacular form of the French personal name <i>Maurice</i> (see   Morris  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Moores","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Moore  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":77,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":86,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":97,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Mores was born in 1472, in England as the daughter of Richard Delabere. She had at least 1 son with Robert Radford."},"et":{"1472–":"1472–Surnud","1472–Female":"1472–Surnud","1462–Male":"1462–Surnud","1495–1578":"1495–1578","1448–1514":"1448–1514","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1448":"1448","1578":"1578","1495":"1495","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Hennock, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Hennock, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1472–":"1472–Kuollut","1472–Female":"1472–Kuollut","1462–Male":"1462–Kuollut","1495–1578":"1495–1578","1448–1514":"1448–1514","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1448":"1448","1578":"1578","1495":"1495","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Hennock, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Hennock, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"1472–":"1472–Décédée","1472–Female":"1472–Décédée","1462–Male":"1462–Décédé","1495–1578":"1495–1578","1448–1514":"1448–1514","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1448":"1448","1578":"1578","1495":"1495","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","Hennock, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Hennock, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Englan